    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "what do you mean by garden goblin? i don't get it. can you just tell me what the actual nutrient deficiency is and how i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I was just using the term \"garden goblin\" as a colloquialism to describe the sneaky, hidden problems that can affect plants. It's a bit of a whimsical way to refer to the common issues that can arise in the garden.\n\nAs for the actual nutrient deficiency, it's possible that your tomato plants are lacking magnesium or calcium. These minerals are essential for healthy plant growth, and a deficiency can cause yellowing leaves, especially on the lower parts of the plant.\n\nTo fix the soil, you can try adding a balanced fertilizer that contains magnesium and calcium. You can also consider getting a soil test to determine the specific nutrient levels in your soil. Some common signs of magnesium deficiency include yellowing leaves, while calcium deficiency can cause blossom end rot, which is a brown or black spot on the fruit.\n\nIt's worth noting that the roots of tomato plants can be quite sensitive, so it's essential to avoid overwatering and ensure good drainage. A well-balanced fertilizer and a healthy soil structure can go a long way in preventing these types of issues.",
