    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok so if it is magnesium i should probably add some epsom salt? and how do i actually check the ph? is there a specific way to do it so i dont mess up the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Epsom salt is a great way to provide magnesium to your tomato plants. Just be sure to use it in moderation, as excessive magnesium can be toxic to plants. A general rule of thumb is to add 1-2 tablespoons of Epsom salt per gallon of water, and then use that solution to water your plants.\n\nAs for checking the pH, it's relatively easy to do. You can purchase a pH test kit at most gardening stores or online. These kits usually include test strips or a pH meter that will give you a quick reading of your soil's pH level.\n\nWhen using a pH test kit, make sure to follow the instructions carefully. You'll typically need to collect a small sample of soil, mix it with water, and then compare the resulting color to the chart provided with the kit. This will give you a rough estimate of your soil's pH level.\n\nIt's also worth noting that the pH range for tomatoes is relatively narrow - between 6.0 and 6.8. If your soil is too acidic or too alkaline, it can affect nutrient availability and plant growth.\n\nOne thing to keep in mind is that pH levels can fluctuate over time, so it's a good idea to test your soil",
      "source": "target",
